---
import SiteLayout from '../../../components/SiteLayout.astro';

const title = 'What does DDR mean in RAM? DDR4 vs DDR5';
const description =
  'DDR4 or DDR5: what is it, which is better and which to buy? A quick gamer guide to RAM, DDR generations and the differences that truly matter.';

const fecha = 'June 12, 2026';
const dateISO = '2026-06-12';
const tiempoLectura = '5 min read';

const secciones = [
  { id: 'que-es-ddr', label: 'What does DDR mean?' },
  { id: 'generaciones', label: 'DDR4 vs DDR5' },
  { id: 'velocidad', label: 'Speed and latency' },
  { id: 'gaming', label: 'Which matters for gaming?' },
  { id: 'cuanta', label: 'How much RAM do you need?' },
  { id: 'dual-channel', label: 'Dual channel: the key trick' },
];
---

<SiteLayout title={`${title} | Monckey Gamer`} description={description} robots="index, follow" article={{ title, dateISO }}>
  <article class="post">
    <a class="category-back" href="/en/blog/">← Back to Blog</a>

    <header class="post-header">
      <span class="post-tag"><span class="post-tag-gg">GG</span> Gamer guide · Hardware</span>
      <h1>What does DDR mean in RAM? DDR4 vs DDR5</h1>
      <p class="post-lead">
        Every time you buy RAM you see DDR4 or DDR5, and nobody explains what changes between them or which to pick.
        Here it is: no jargon, just what matters for gaming.
      </p>
      <div class="post-meta">
        <span>{fecha}</span>
        <span class="post-meta-dot"></span>
        <span>{tiempoLectura}</span>
      </div>
    </header>

    <nav class="post-toc" aria-label="Article contents">
      <span class="post-toc-title">In this article</span>
      <ul>
        {secciones.map((s) => (
          <li><a href={`#${s.id}`}>{s.label}</a></li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    </nav>

    <div class="post-body">
      <section id="que-es-ddr">
        <h2>What does DDR mean?</h2>
        <p>
          DDR stands for <strong>Double Data Rate</strong>. It means the
          memory transfers data twice per clock cycle: once on the rising edge
          and once on the falling edge. That makes it twice as efficient as old SDR RAM.
        </p>
        <p>
          The number that follows (DDR4, DDR5) indicates the generation. Each new generation brings more
          speed, lower power draw and more bandwidth, but the physical slot changes:
          <strong>DDR4 and DDR5 are not compatible with each other</strong>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="generaciones">
        <h2>DDR4 vs DDR5: key differences</h2>
        <div class="post-table-wrap">
          <table class="post-table">
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Feature</th>
                <th>DDR4</th>
                <th>DDR5</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td>Standard speed</td><td>2133–3600 MHz</td><td>4800–7200+ MHz</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Bandwidth</td><td>Up to ~51 GB/s</td><td>Up to ~100+ GB/s</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Typical voltage</td><td>1.35 V</td><td>1.1 V (more efficient)</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Compatibility</td><td>AM4, Intel 10th/11th/12th gen</td><td>AM5, Intel 12th/13th/14th gen</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Price</td><td>More affordable</td><td>Still a slight premium</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p class="post-note">
          Note: DDR4 and DDR5 use different physical slots. They are not interchangeable.
          Your motherboard determines which type you need.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="velocidad">
        <h2>Speed and latency: what nobody explains</h2>
        <p>
          MHz speed is not the only number that matters. <strong>CAS latency (CL)</strong>
          indicates how many cycles the RAM takes to respond. Faster RAM with higher latency
          can perform the same or worse than slower RAM with low latency.
        </p>
        <p>
          The key figure is the <strong>absolute latency in nanoseconds</strong>: CL ÷ (Speed MHz / 2000).
          For example, DDR4 3200 CL16 = 10 ns. DDR5 4800 CL40 = 16.7 ns. The DDR4 responds faster
          despite the lower frequency.
        </p>
        <p>
          The best modern DDR5 options like the
          <a href="/en/ram-memory/corsair-vengeance-rgb-rs-16gb-6000mhz-1/">Corsair Vengeance DDR5 6000MHz</a>
          balance speed and latency for the best real-world result.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="gaming">
        <h2>Which matters more for gaming: DDR4 or DDR5?</h2>
        <p>
          In pure gaming, the difference between well-configured DDR4 and DDR5 is small (5–10% in most
          games). What truly matters:
        </p>
        <ul class="post-list">
          <li>
            <strong>On the AM4 platform (Ryzen 5000):</strong> use DDR4. The
            <a href="/en/ram-memory/gigastone-game-pro-32gb-3200mhz-2/">Gigastone 32GB DDR4 3200MHz</a> or
            <a href="/en/ram-memory/teamgroup-t-force-delta-rgb-16gb-3600mhz-4/">TEAMGROUP 16GB DDR4 3600MHz</a>
            are excellent options.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>On AM5 (Ryzen 7000) or Intel 12th gen+:</strong> use DDR5.
            The recommended minimum speed is 5600 MHz so you leave no performance on the table.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section id="cuanta">
        <h2>How much RAM do you need for gaming?</h2>
        <div class="post-table-wrap">
          <table class="post-table">
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Use case</th>
                <th>Recommended RAM</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td>Basic gaming (1080p)</td><td>16 GB</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Gaming + streaming</td><td>32 GB</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Gaming + video editing</td><td>32–64 GB</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Demanding games (Starfield, MSFS)</td><td>32 GB</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="dual-channel">
        <h2>Dual channel: the trick that changes performance the most</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Dual channel</strong> means installing RAM in pairs (2×8 GB instead of 1×16 GB)
          to double the available bandwidth. It is the free change that gains you the most FPS in gaming.
        </p>
        <p>
          On AMD processors with integrated graphics (APUs) the difference can reach 40%.
          On discrete builds, the gain is 5–15% in CPU-bound games like Cyberpunk 2077 or
          Microsoft Flight Simulator.
        </p>
        <p>
          Always install the RAM in the correct slots (check your board's manual: usually
          slots A2 and B2). See our full
          <a href="/en/ram-memory/">RAM memory</a> catalog with 2-module kit options.
        </p>
      </section>
    </div>

    <aside class="post-cta">
      <h3>Ready to upgrade your RAM?</h3>
      <p>Browse our DDR4 and DDR5 memory selection at the best price with Amazon shipping.</p>
      <a class="btn" href="/en/ram-memory/">View RAM memory</a>
    </aside>
  </article>
</SiteLayout>

<style>
  .post { max-width: 760px; margin: 0 auto; }
  .post-header { margin: 18px 0 32px; }
  .post-tag { display: inline-flex; align-items: center; gap: 7px; font-size: 0.68rem; font-weight: 500; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.14em; color: #8aa0b8; }
  .post-tag-gg { font-weight: 800; letter-spacing: 0.05em; color: #7cffcb; border: 1px solid rgba(124,255,203,0.3); border-radius: 5px; padding: 1px 5px; font-size: 0.62rem; }
  .post-header h1 { margin: 18px 0 16px; font-size: clamp(1.6rem,6vw,2.8rem); line-height: 1.15; overflow-wrap: break-word; }
  .post-lead { margin: 0 0 18px; color: #c8d8e8; font-size: 1.1rem; line-height: 1.7; }
  .post-meta { display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 12px; color: #8aa0b8; font-size: 0.9rem; }
  .post-meta-dot { width: 4px; height: 4px; border-radius: 50%; background: #8aa0b8; }
  .post-toc { margin: 0 0 40px; padding: 24px 28px; border-radius: 20px; background: rgba(255,255,255,0.02); border: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08); }
  .post-toc-title { display: block; font-size: 0.75rem; font-weight: 600; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.1em; color: #7cffcb; margin-bottom: 14px; }
  .post-toc ul { margin: 0; padding: 0; list-style: none; display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(2,minmax(0,1fr)); gap: 10px 24px; }
  .post-toc a { color: #c8d8e8; text-decoration: none; font-size: 0.95rem; transition: color 0.2s ease; }
  .post-toc a:hover { color: #7cffcb; }
  .post-body section { margin-bottom: 40px; scroll-margin-top: 24px; }
  .post-body h2 { font-size: 1.5rem; color: #e6f7ff; margin: 0 0 16px; padding-left: 14px; border-left: 3px solid #7cffcb; }
  .post-body p { color: #c8d8e8; line-height: 1.8; margin: 0 0 16px; }
  .post-body strong { color: #e6f7ff; }
  .post-body a { color: #7cffcb; text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 3px; }
  .post-list { margin: 0 0 16px; padding: 0; list-style: none; display: grid; gap: 12px; }
  .post-list li { color: #c8d8e8; line-height: 1.7; padding-left: 26px; position: relative; }
  .post-list li::before { content: ""; position: absolute; left: 4px; top: 11px; width: 7px; height: 7px; border-radius: 50%; background: #7cffcb; }
  .post-table-wrap { margin: 0 0 18px; overflow-x: auto; border-radius: 16px; border: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08); }
  .post-table { width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.95rem; }
  .post-table th { text-align: left; padding: 14px 20px; color: #7cffcb; font-size: 0.78rem; font-weight: 600; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.06em; background: rgba(255,255,255,0.03); border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08); }
  .post-table td { padding: 13px 20px; color: #c8d8e8; border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.05); }
  .post-table tbody tr:last-child td { border-bottom: none; }
  .post-table td:first-child { color: #e6f7ff; font-weight: 500; }
  .post-note { background: rgba(27,183,255,0.06); border: 1px solid rgba(27,183,255,0.18); border-radius: 14px; padding: 16px 20px; color: #c8d8e8 !important; font-size: 0.95rem; }
  .post-cta { margin-top: 48px; padding: 36px; border-radius: 24px; text-align: center; background: linear-gradient(135deg,rgba(0,255,225,0.06),rgba(27,183,255,0.06)); border: 1px solid rgba(124,255,203,0.15); }
  .post-cta h3 { margin: 0 0 8px; font-size: 1.4rem; color: #e6f7ff; }
  .post-cta p { margin: 0 0 20px; color: #c8d8e8; }
  @media (max-width: 640px) {
    .post-toc { padding: 20px; margin-bottom: 28px; }
    .post-toc ul { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
    .post-lead { font-size: 1rem; }
    .post-meta { flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 8px; }
    .post-body section { margin-bottom: 32px; }
    .post-body h2 { font-size: 1.3rem; }
    .post-table { font-size: 0.85rem; }
    .post-table th { padding: 11px 12px; font-size: 0.7rem; }
    .post-table td { padding: 10px 12px; }
